I'm sure everyone here has seen a lot of coronavirus coverage with rising statistics every day.  The main thing I have to add is that I think insufficient weight in the public discourse about numbers is being given to the fact that confirmed cases is a deeply lagging indicator of the rate of new infections in an area (which tracks with the risk that one might be infected when going about one's normal life).  Which means that in many places the confirmed numbers are low and one might think coronavirus isn't present yet, we should still be adjusting our habits.

Last night, I did a more detailed mathematical analysis looking at several data sources (one of the best is https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_outbreak_data/Italy_medical_cases since it has regional breakdowns) to predict out how far in time the SF Bay Area likely is from the kind of major outbreak described there.  The conclusions are, frankly, alarming.

There are 3 regions of Italy that have been at ~100 confirmed cases for long enough to be useful for projecting forward: LOM (Lombardy), EMR, and VEN. Of those, LOM was at ~100 confirmed cases 16 days ago and is now at 5800 confirmed cases with 468 deaths; EMR and VEN were at ~100 confirmed cases 11 days ago and now between them total 2300 confirmed cases and 110 deaths.  We're at ~100 confirmed cases in the SF Bay Area right now, which suggests the Bay Area's future for the next 2 weeks will look a lot like what we've seen in Northern Italy (!).  While it's very hard to predict the future with these things as both past and future data on a lot of variables (testing procedure, public health response, etc.), I'm just a math person and not an epidemiologist, and I of course really really hope things don't play out how I currently predict... there's strong evidential support for that conclusion.

The other thing that's clear is many of the now 10000 confirmed cases in Italy were probably contracted during the weeks when the confirmed case number felt relatively small (dozens to maybe low hundreds) and some public officials and media were still saying "We're canceling large events but otherwise you can mostly continue life as normal because there are few cases in our community", as they have been in places in America.  The data suggests that regions will hit the point where hundreds or thousands of people are being infected each week in a given community well before it feels that way (a lot of places have gone from ~2 confirmed cases to the ~100 we have in the Bay Area now in a week or two, and even 100 feels really small in a region with millions of people).  And then there's other places, like Iran, where authorities pretended there were no cases until the numbers were so large they couldn't pretend anymore.

A big part of what's behind rapid spread is that people are contagious before they have intense enough symptoms that they might either worry that they have coronavirus or are tested, which means governments might be basing their decisions on confirmed case data that is a few doublings old at any given time.  Certainly the public is!  As a result, too many people (both unwittingly infected or not) are still riding public transit, going to restaurants, working out at the gym, etc. at times when in fact an outbreak is happening in their community.

Given that data (and also several super depressing on-the-ground reports from Italy like this translated Twitter thread: https://threadreaderapp.com/thread/1237142891077697538.html), I would encourage everyone to start adjusting their habits now as though outbreaks of a similar scale to Lombardy will be documented in hundreds of places over the next month, potentially including where you live.  In particular, it's really important to understand that confirmed test results one reads about in the news are a lagging indicator of the situation (since it can take weeks for an infected person to have symptoms, wait for those to be severe enough they think it's not just a cold, go to a hospital, be tested, etc.), and so one should be very cautious about inferring that a lack of (many) confirmed cases in one's area means coronavirus isn't already spreading there.

Based on all this data, I think right now is the time for everyone to, without panicking, accept that there's a pandemic happening and we need to change our habits and start staying at home to the maximal extent we reasonably can.  At least in SF, shifting one's habits a couple weeks from now will
